<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c6">Outrage Over Teenager's Death Erupts on Social Media</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">BYLINE: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">By SAMANTHA STOREY</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">SECTION: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">Section ; Column 0; National Desk; Pg. </SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">LENGTH: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">409 words</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">The weekend shooting of Michael Brown, 18, who was killed by a police officer in Ferguson, Mo., a St. Louis suburb, is drawing outrage on social media outlets such as Twitter and Facebook. The shooting is now being investigated by the F.B.I. </SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">There are short video clips and Vines being posted by protesters at a rally on Monday, carrying signs like the one below that says, ''I can be killed by the police but shouldn't.''</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">&quot;Justice Now&quot; https://t.co/axQRbwb4bs -- Antonio French (@AntonioFrench) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">There are also photos of the rally.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Police standing by #Ferguson pic.twitter.com/6XrLfsM7Lo -- Ryan Schuessler (@RyanSchuessler1) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Another photograph being shared is reportedly of the Mr. Brown's father, Louis Head.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Tragic: Unarmed Black Teen Shot Dead By St. Louis Police [Photos + Video] http://t.co/xfrIeGJidN pic.twitter.com/fWGrjwq0PJ -- DallasBlack.com (@DallasBlackcom) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Users are also sharing images of Monday's front page of The St. Louis Post-Dispatch.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">ST.Louis front page pic.twitter.com/BxhzMwGfji -- Alik (@alik_rainey) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">The St. Louis County police posted a response to the protests on Facebook.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">In reference to the Ferguson Police Department shooting which occurred yesterday, we are investigating the... http://t.co/2ZJVPlpxdP -- St. Louis County PD (@stlcountypd) August 10, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">The St. Louis American, a weekly newspaper, posted a photo of the protesters on Sunday night.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Crowd encourage each other to stand as one. #Unity! Crowd chants, &quot;Enough is Enough!&quot; #MikeBrown #Ferguson pic.twitter.com/cq8OpJ1NKd -- St. Louis American (@StLouisAmerican) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">A popular hashtag is #iftheygunnedmedown. Mostly being used by young African-Americans, each Twitter post with the hashtag shows two pictures. The first is something positive, such as a high school graduation, the poster flanked by relatives, diploma in hand; the other photo is more candid and shows a face enveloped by smoke or a swig from a bottle of whiskey. The point is the contrast, and the juxtaposition. Some of the images are graphic, but here are two that show the sentiment of the discussion.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">''@TroyTrippy: #IfTheyGunnedMeDown pic.twitter.com/jOvSAaERik'' they can't use the first one cus of copyright infringement lls -- beezus (@rosaSPARKS____) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">''@Gifty_Presenter: #IfTheyGunnedMeDown what picture would they use. pic.twitter.com/g7uTANRGTm'' im actually finished -- Theo Tkordz (@esiri_k) August 11, 2014</SPAN></P>
